# Module 01 – Footprinting & Reconnaissance

This was the first module I seriously sat down with, and honestly it took me a while 
to realize how much information is publicly available about any target before you even 
touch a single tool.

My local lab setup: Kali Linux running on VirtualBox, with a separate Windows VM 
acting as the target machine.

---

## What I was trying to do

The goal was simple — gather as much information about my target as possible 
without actively interacting with it (passive recon), and then move to active recon 
using actual tools.

---

## Passive Recon – Starting with Google Dorks

Before opening Kali, I just opened a browser and tried some Google dorks on a 
dummy domain I created locally. The idea was to understand what an attacker 
sees before they even begin.

Some dorks I practiced with:

- `site:target.com filetype:pdf` – finds exposed documents  
- `intitle:"index of"` – looks for open directories  
- `inurl:admin` – finds admin panels  

It felt weirdly simple. Like, you don't need any fancy tool to start finding 
things — just knowing how to search differently is enough.

---

## Active Recon – theHarvester

Next I ran theHarvester on my test domain from Kali terminal:

```bash
theHarvester -d testdomain.local -b google
```

Didn't get much since it was local, but I understood the flow — 
it scrapes emails, subdomains, IPs linked to the domain from public sources.

For a real domain this would return a lot. Good starting point before 
jumping into Nmap.

---

## DNS Footprinting

This was actually interesting. I used `nslookup` and `dig` on my local DNS setup:

```bash
nslookup testdomain.local
dig testdomain.local ANY
```

`dig ANY` returns all DNS record types at once — A, MX, NS, TXT. 
Once I saw the NS records, I tried a zone transfer just to see if it's misconfigured:

```bash
dig axfr testdomain.local @nameserver
```

In a real misconfigured server, this dumps the entire DNS zone — 
basically handing you the internal network map. Scary how common this used to be.

---

## What I learned

Footprinting is less about tools and more about patience. 
The more time you spend here, the less guessing you do later. 
I used to want to jump straight to scanning — now I get why recon comes first.

